  "prompt": "What is the minimum level of mathematical proficiency required to graduate from West Point?",
  "response": "To graduate from the United States Military Academy at West Point, cadets typically need to demonstrate proficiency in various areas of mathematics. The specific mathematical skills expected include calculus and algebra, as these subjects are foundational for many aspects of military science, engineering, and operations. \n\nWhile there isn't a defined \"minimum level\" in terms of standardized testing scores like the SAT or ACT that guarantees admission or graduation, West Point's curriculum includes rigorous math courses such as calculus I and II, differential equations, and linear algebra. Cadets are expected to complete a minimum number of mathematics credits as part of their core curriculum. \n\nSuccessful completion of these courses is necessary not only for graduation but also for ensuring that graduates can apply mathematical concepts in their military training and future careers. Therefore, a solid understanding of high school mathematics up to calculus, along with the ability to handle college-level math, is critical for cadets.",
